<TEXT>
the debate over president bushs power to send 
american troops into combat in the mideast without congressional 
approval is heating up as international support grows for using 
force to free kuwait 
even as bush proclaimed he is very very close to having 
enough support for a united nations resolution authorizing force 
against iraqi forces in kuwait democratic congressional leaders 
again said they must have a say on whether to send american gis 
into combat 
i think if a decision is made to change that policy to seek 
an offensive military action by the united states against iraq 
then there will have to be prior approval by the congress and i 
believe extensive debate in the congress and in the country 
said senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine on friday 
bush has pledged to consult with congress but has indicated he 
might not provide advance notice of any military action or seek 
advance approval 
house speaker thomas foley dwash joined mitchell in urging 
bush to seek congressional approval before committing us forces 
to fighting and said the presidents chances of winning that 
backing would improve if the united nations endorsed the use of 
force 
it would have some significant impact if the united nations 
granted such a resolution foley told reporters 
if the un resolution is adopted then i would hope congress 
would reconvene and take similar action said senate republican 
leader bob dole of kansas the president ought to have that 
authority and have the congress behind him 
such a course would lessen the chance of an afterthefact fight 
over the right to declare war but there still may be opposition in 
congress to endorsing an attack 
mitchell agreed with foley that a un resolution would give 
bush better odds at winning a congressional endorsement but said 
it would not guarantee one 
it would depend upon the circumstances that exist at the 
time said mitchell 
mitchell in a speech earlier this week acknowledged a 
reasonable basis for argument on both sides over whether the 
constitution requires the president to get congress approval 
before ordering us troops into hostilities 
the debate also has split legal scholars 
the constitutional argument not to put too fine a point on 
it is almost certainly wrong yale law school professor stephen 
l carter said in a recent essay published in the washington post 
there is nothing in the history of the ratification of the 
constitution to suggest that the founders imagined that a 
congressional declaration of war would be needed whenever american 
troops fought an engagement 
taking the opposite view are attorneys at the center for 
constitutional rights which is representing 45 house democrats in 
a suit seeking an injunction prohibiting bush from ordering us 
troops to attack iraqi forces unless congress gave its approval 
if the president takes it upon himself to initiate such a 
war without the unequivocal consent of congress the victim of 
iraqi aggression will be not just kuwait but the constitution of 
the united states the center contended in the lawsuit due for a 
dec 4 hearing 
