<TEXT>
service in the allvolunteer army no longer is 
entirely voluntary 
because of the persian gulf buildup for the first time since 
the draft was abolished in 1973 the army has suspended laws that 
normally allow officers and enlisted members to leave when their 
service obligations are fulfilled 
the army announced friday that the demands of operation desert 
shield have forced it to halt all voluntary retirements and to 
prevent enlisted personnel from leaving 
the move will mean that about 5500 people per month who 
otherwise would have left the service will be forced to stay on 
indefinitely 
the decision was approved by defense secretary dick cheney it 
is an extraordinary move that will upset the plans and expectations 
of many soldiers including those who had lined up civilian jobs in 
anticipation of retiring or who had planned to enter college after 
completing their enlistments 
the army also said it is freezing indefinitely all transfers of 
soldiers from overseas to bases in the united states and is 
cancelling the traditional christmas vacation period for all army 
training centers and military schools 
the cancellation of holiday vacations will affect 22 army 
institutions not including the west point ny military academy 
included are seven basic training posts such as fort jackson sc 
and advanced training centers such as the artillery school at fort 
sill okla the infantry training post at fort benning ga and 
the personnel administration and finance school at fort benjamin 
harrison ind said army spokeswoman capt barbara goodno 
army officials offered those examples of affected installations 
but declined to provide a complete list 
the freeze on transfers will affect between 1000 and 1500 
people per month said an army official who discussed the measures 
on condition he not be identified 
the combination of measures is designed to keep the army at the 
highest possible state of readiness in case additional 
reinforcements are needed in the persian gulf crisis the official 
said it reflects a view among senior military leaders that the 
us commitment to the gulf will be longstanding he said 
ive got an unprecedented deployment underway in saudi 
arabia which required the army to take the extreme step of 
preventing soldiers and officers from leaving the service the 
official said 
about 130000 army personnel are deployed in saudi arabia and 
another 100000 are heading there 
also on friday the marine corps disclosed it invoked a measure 
on nov 8 that means as many as 12000 marines both regular and 
reserve could be prevented from leaving the service even though 
they were due to retire or end their service obligations unlike 
the army the marines will not apply the measure servicewide said 
maj nancy j laluntas a spokeswoman at marine corps headquarters 
the navy has not taken any measures to force sailors to stay in 
the service but it has not ruled out doing so in the future said 
lt beci brenton a navy spokeswoman 
the marines also announced friday activation of another 2377 
reservists for desert shield nearly all will report for duty with 
the 2nd marine expeditionary force at camp lejeune nc to 
reinforce approximately 45000 marines in the gulf 
president bush on aug 22 gave cheney legal authority to retain 
members of the armed forces on duty in the gulf who reach their 
retirement or reenlistment dates but the authority was limited to 
those soldiers and officers directly involved in desert shield 
in taking its action friday the army went a step further and 
applied the authority to everyone in the service 
the army since sept 1 had used the authority on a limited 
basis retaining about 2000 personnel per month who otherwise 
would have retired or not renewed their service contracts 
the army said there will be three exceptions to the mandatory 
extensions of service officers who face mandatory retirement for 
medical or other reasons soldiers discharged for reasons of 
incompetence or other failings and hardship cases 
</TEXT>
