<TEXT>
manufacturing japanese cars in the united 
states cost america 36000 jobs in 1988 and 1989 congressional 
auditors say 
the general accounting office of congress said friday that new 
japaneseowned factories in the united states generally are more 
efficient than us automakers and require fewer workers to produce 
the same number of cars 
the gao said some 11000 jobs were lost in 1989 and 25000 the 
previous year 
fewer jobs were lost last year in part because the japanese 
manufacturers bought more parts from us sources the watchdog 
agency said 
the gao report was prepared at the request of sen carl levin 
dmich and rep marcy kaptur dohio 
the gao said it used a complicated formula based on the 
assumption that cars produced in japaneseowned us factories 
displaced both imported japanese cars and cars that otherwise would 
have been sold by general motors ford and chrysler 
its report said japaneseaffiliated factories in america turned 
out 1131000 cars in 1989 and calculated that this provided 
66000 jobs but displaced 77000 other jobs for a net loss of 
11000 
the japanese factories used us sources for 505 percent of 
their parts and components in 1989 compared to 385 percent the 
previous year the gao said 
the gao said the us big three car companies employed 4151 
people per 200000 cars of production compared to only 2613 by 
japaneseaffiliated automakers 
</TEXT>
