a rare strain of the aids virus could get into 
the nations blood supply but the us centers for disease control 
says its too rare to spend money trying to detect it 
only 18 known cases of the strain known as human 
immunodeficiency virus type 2 hiv2 exist in the united states 
tests for the more common aids virus hiv1 usually detect the 
rarer strain predominantly found in west africa 
a study of more than 25000 blood samples detected no blood 
donors with hiv2 infection the cdc concluded that adding hiv2 
tests to routine blood donor screening wouldnt be worth the cost 
of more than 60 million a year 
