<TEXT>
here are sketches of the main candidates 
in polands first direct democratic presidential election sunday 
 
lech walesaequals 
the 47yearold with an astonishing mix of political instinct 
and personal charisma has arguably done more than any other 
individual to topple communism and says the presidency is his next 
responsiblity he contends even more must be reformed if poland is 
to become a true democracy 
born to a dirtpoor farm family in a remote hamlet walesa had a 
tradeschool education when he drifted to the baltic port of gdansk 
and took a job at the lenin shipyard in 1967 
increasingly incensed by the workers lot and dispiriting 
totalitarian rule especially after the bloody repression of 
strikes in 1970 walesa lost one job after another to his 
activism he was unemployed and outside the strikebound shipyard 
when he made his famous leap over the gate to lead solidaritys 
founding in 1980 
interned after martial law in december 1981 and awarded the 
nobel peace prize in 1983 walesa maneuvered the solidarity 
movement through years of repression to its takeover of the 
government in 1989 
after creating the solidarity government against dubious 
colleagues advice walesa found himself on the political sidelines 
in gdansk but increasingly alarmed by social discontent apathy and 
disaffection with the new government 
he can be autocratic and contradictory demagogic 
irresponsible and uncultured to his critics but the walesa of the 
twinkling eyes mesmerizing speech tothepeople style and 
enormous courage still holds immense sway 
 
tadeusz mazowieckiequals 
the 63yearold prime minister became eastern europes first 
noncommunist government leader in august 1989 launched the 
regions most dramatic economic overhaul on jan 1 and says poland 
needs his team to stay and finish the job 
mazowieckis devout catholicism led him to oppose the 
thencommunist government during the 1950s he founded the 
influential club of catholic intellectuals in warsaw and the 
monthly magazine wiez 
in 1961 he joined the parliament delegation of znak a tiny 
officially condoned independent group protected by the church but 
eventually his principles clashed with the communists bounds of 
tolerance after he demanded an investigation into the 1970 
killings of strikeing workers he was barred from reelection 
mazowiecki joined walesa in the founding days of solidarity in 
august 1980 he brought a letter of support from intellectuals to 
the strikebound gdansk shipyard and stayed imprisoned during 
martial law the taciturn lawyer negotiated with communists in 1989 
at historic talks and submitted the court motion winning back 
solidaritys legal status 
proposed for prime minister by walesa mazowiecki has become 
increasingly confident though never comfortable under the 
international spotlight but the two split along with the 
onceunited solidarity movement over the whether mazowieckis 
deliberate reasoned course to reform is too slow 
 
stanislaw tyminskiequals 
the virtually unknown 42yearold emigre with polish canadian 
and peruvian citizenship grabbed the spotlight late in the campaign 
when one poll showed him in second place trailing only walesa 
tyminski says he left poland penniless 21 years ago going first 
to sweden as a tourist and then emigrating to canada where he 
became a millionaire he started a cable television outfit and a 
restaurant in the amazon port of iquitos peru and then returned 
to canada where he runs transduction ltd a computer automation 
firm near toronto he leads the libertarian party of canada a 
fringe party that has no representative in parliament 
tyminski financing his own campaign attracted supporters 
disenchanted with polands drastic economic reforms who responded 
to his harsh criticism of the government but his credentials went 
largely unchallenged until his surge in the polls then journalists 
started to question his long absence from poland and state 
prosecutors launched a slander investigation after he accused 
mazowiecki of treason against the nation 
</TEXT>
