<DOCNO> AP901124-0098 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
defying international appeals japan launched the 
fourth season of its controversial research whaling program 
saturday with plans to kill up to 330 whales 
environmentalists charge the program is a cover for continued 
commercial whaling 
the mother ship nisshin maru no 3 left saturday for the 
antarctic ocean where it is to be joined by three smaller boats 
for four months of whaling kyodo news service reported 
they officially plan to catch 300 minke whales a relatively 
abundant smaller species the research program allows up to 330 
animals to be killed 
in july japan norway and iceland appealed unsuccessfully at a 
meeting of the international whaling commission for minkes to be 
excluded from the commissions moratorium on commercial whaling 
nobuyuki yagi a fishery agency official said japan hopes 
information about minke populations gathered by the fleet this 
season will encourage the commission to reevaluate the moratorium 
instituted in 1986 after many of the great whale species were 
hunted close to extinction 
japanese officials say whales must be killed during the research 
to accurately determine their age sex childbearing state diet 
and health 
environmentalists say nonlethal research methods are available 
such as skin samplings and sighting studies 
japan officially stopped its commercial whaling at the end of 
the 198687 season when it caught 1941 whales it then began a 
program of research whaling which is permitted under the whaling 
commissions charter 
japanese whalers killed 273 animals in the first year of the 
research program 241 in the second and 330 in the third 
at its meeting this year the commission passed nonbinding 
resolutions questioning whether japans research program was 
scientifically accurate and urging it to use nonlethal methods 
wherever possible officials said 
although japanese whaling officials previously said at least 825 
whales must be caught each year to make the program scientifically 
valid japanese experts recalculated the sampling error in response 
to the iwc resolutions and determined that 300 was sufficient yagi 
said 
japan also appealed at the iwc meeting for permission to hunt 50 
minke whales commercially each year along its coast saying small 
traditional whaling communities had been damaged by the moratorium 
yagi said but that proposal also was rejected 
the minke reaches about 30 feet in length and eight tons in 
weight and is the smallest of the commercially sought great 
whales the commission estimates there are about 760000 minkes in 
the antarctic and about 83000 in the north atlantic 
officials say whaling also is an important part of the japanese 
diet and culture japan is the worlds largest consumer of whale 
meat and whales provided 23 percent of the nations meat when 
japanese whaling was at its peak in the early 1960s 
whale meat is now considered a delicacy because of its limited 
supply 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

