demonstrations but some scuffles erupted when the progovernment 
rally began to disperse 
several hundred opposition supporters blocked the capitals main 
boulevard by sitting or lying in the road to block the way of 
progovernment demonstrators 
helmeted police with nightsticks called on the protesters to 
clear the street but refrained from using force to disperse them 
after about an hour the police withdrew and the protesters 
dispersed peacefully 
opposition leaders claim they would triumph in new elections 
they have repeatedly rejected lukanovs requests to join a broad 
socialistled coalition government insisting instead on naming the 
premier and holding key ministries 
the socialist party won free elections in june and holds 210 
seats in parliament the opposition union has 144 seats 
lukanov repeated he was open to dialogue with the opposition and 
reiterated his determination to push through badly needed reforms 
to turn around the failing economy 
however he warned that he could not promise easy days under 
the tough reforms the program will be difficult even cruel 
